==Morning sickness as a defense mechanism==
Morning sickness is believed to be an [[natural selection|evolved trait]] that protects the fetus against [[toxin]]s ingested by the mother.<ref>{{Cite book
 | last=Hook | first=E. B. | author-link=
 | chapter=Changes in tobacco smoking and ingestion of alcohol and caffeinated beverages during early pregnancy: are these consequences, in part, of feto-protective mechanisms diminishing maternal exposure to embryotoxins?
 | date= | year=1976
 | editor-last=Kelly
 | editor-first=S.
 | title=Birth Defects: Risks and Consequences
 | volume=
 | pages= 173–181
 | publisher=Academic Press
 | publication-date=1976
 | isbn=
 }}
</ref>
<ref>{{cite book |last=Profet | first=Margie| editor1-last=Barkow| editor2-last=Cosmides| editor3-last=Tooby
|title= The Adapted Mind: Evolutionary Psychology and the Generation of Culture|publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1992 |pages=327–365 |chapter=Pregnancy Sickness as Adaptation: A Deterrent to Maternal Ingestion of Teratogens |isbn=
|editor-first=Jerome
|editor3-first=Leda
|editor1-first=John}}</ref> Many plants contain chemical toxins that serve as a deterrent to being eaten.  Adult humans, like other animals, have defenses against plant toxins, including extensive arrays of detoxification [[enzyme]]s manufactured by the [[liver]] and the surface tissues of various other organs.  In the fetus, these defenses are not yet fully developed, and even small doses of plant toxins that have negligible effects on the adult can be harmful or lethal to the embryo.<ref name="Beck">{{cite book
  | last = Beck | first1 = F.
  | title = Human Embryology and Genetics
  | publisher = Blackwell Scientific
  | location =
  | year = 1973
  | isbn =  }}</ref> Pregnancy sickness causes women to experience nausea when exposed to the smell or taste of foods that are likely to contain toxins injurious to the fetus, even though they may be harmless to her.

There is considerable evidence in support of this theory, including:<ref name="Nesse">{{cite book |last1=Nesse |first1= Randolphe M
|authorlink=George C. Williams|last2=Williams
|first2=George C |editor= |others= |title= Why We Get Sick |year=1996
|origmonth= |url= |format= |accessdate= |edition= First
|series= |volume= |date= |month=
|publisher= Vintage Books
|location= New York |language= |isbn= |oclc= |doi= |id= |pages= 290 |chapter= |chapterurl= |quote= }}</ref>
<ref name="Pepper">{{cite journal
  | last1 = Pepper
  | first1 = GV | first2 = Gillian V.
  | last2 = Roberts | first3 = S. Craig
  | title = Rates of nausea and vomiting in pregnancy and dietary characteristics across populations
  | journal = Proceedings of the Royal Society B
  | volume = 273
  | issue = 1601
  | pages = 2675–2679
  | year = 2006
  | pmid = 17002954
  | pmc = 1635459
  | doi = 10.1098/rsbp.2006.3633}}</ref>
* Morning sickness is very common among pregnant women, which argues in favor of its being a functional adaptation and against the idea that it is a [[pathology]].
* Fetal vulnerability to toxins peaks at around 3 months, which is also the time of peak susceptibility to morning sickness.
* There is a good correlation between toxin concentrations in foods, and the tastes and odors that cause revulsion.

Women who have ''no'' morning sickness are more likely to [[miscarriage|miscarry]].<ref>{{cite journal | last = Chan | first = Ronna L. et al. | last2 = Olshan | first2 = A. F. | last3 = Savitz | first3 = D. A. | last4 = Herring | first4 = A. H. | last5 = Daniels | first5 = J. L. | last6 = Peterson | first6 = H. B. | last7 = Martin | first7 = S. L. | title = Severity and duration of nausea and vomiting symptoms in pregnancy and spontaneous abortion | journal = Human Reproduction | volume = 25| pages = 2907–12| date = Sept. 22, 2010| pmid = 20861299| issue  = 11|url=http://humrep.oxfordjournals.org/content/early/2010/09/22/humrep.deq260 | doi= 10.1093/humrep/deq260 | pmc = 3140259}}</ref> This may be because such women are more likely to ingest substances that are harmful to the fetus.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Sherman | first = Paul W. | last2=Flaxman | first2 = Samuel M. | title = Nausea and vomiting of pregnancy in an evolutionary perspective | journal = Am J Obstet Gynecol |volume = 186 | pages = S190–S197 | year = 2002| pmid = 12011885| issue = 5 | doi = 10.1067/mob.2002.122593}}</ref>

In addition to protecting the fetus, morning sickness may also protect the mother.  Pregnant women's [[immune system]]s are suppressed during pregnancy, it is presumed to reduce the chances of [[transplant rejection|rejecting]] tissues of their own offspring.<ref>{{cite journal
  | last = Haig | first = David
  | author-link = David Haig (biologist)
  | title = Genetic conflicts in human pregnancy
  | journal = Quarterly Review of Biology
  | volume = 68
  | pages = 495–532
  | date = October 1993
  | pmid = 8115596
  | issue = 4
| doi=10.1086/418300}}</ref> Because of this, animal products containing [[parasite]]s and harmful bacteria can be especially dangerous to pregnant women.  There is evidence that morning sickness is often triggered by animal products including meat and fish.<ref>{{cite journal
  | first1 = Samuel M.
  | last1 = Flaxman
  | first2 = Paul W.
  | last2 = Sherman
  | authorlink =
  | title = Morning sickness: a mechanism for protecting mother and embryo
  | journal = Quarterly Review of Biology
  | volume = 75
  | pages = 113–148
  | date = June 2000
  | pmid = 10858967
  | issue = 2
| doi=10.1086/393377}}</ref>

If morning sickness is a defense mechanism against the ingestion of toxins, the prescribing of [[anti-nausea drugs|anti-nausea medication]] to pregnant women may have the undesired [[side effect]] of causing birth defects or miscarriages by encouraging harmful dietary choices.<ref name="Nesse"/> On the other hand, many domestic vegetables have been purposely [[plant breeding|bred]] to have lower levels of toxins than in the distant past, and so the level of threat to the embryo may not be as high as it was when the defense mechanism first evolved.<ref>{{cite journal
  | first1 = Mike
  | last1 = Martin
  | authorlink =
  | title = Margie Profet's Unfinished Symphony
  | journal = Weekly Scientist
  | volume =
  | pages =
  | date = June 29, 2009}}</ref>

==Treatments==
There is no evidence to demonstrate the effectiveness of home treatments and a lack of high quality evidence generally regarding the treatment of morning sickness.<ref>{{cite journal |author= Matthews A, Dowswell T, Haas DM, Doyle M, O'Mathúna DP |title= Interventions for nausea and vomiting in early pregnancy |journal=Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews |volume=2010 |issue=9 |pages= CD007575 |year=2010 |pmid= 20824863 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD007575.pub2 |url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/o/cochrane/clsysrev/articles/CD007575/frame.html |editor1-last= Matthews |editor1-first= Anne}}</ref>

===Medications===
A number of [[antiemetic]]s are effective and safe in pregnancy including: [[pyridoxine/doxylamine]], [[antihistamines]] (such as [[diphenhydramine]]), and [[phenothiazines]] (such as [[promethazine]]).<ref name=BMJ2011>{{cite journal|last=Jarvis|first=S|coauthors=Nelson-Piercy, C|title=Management of nausea and vomiting in pregnancy.|journal=BMJ (Clinical research ed.)|date=2011 Jun 17|volume=342|pages=d3606|pmid=21685438}}</ref> With respect to effectiveness it is unknown if one is superior to another.<ref name=BMJ2011/> In the [http://www.fda.gov/NewsEvents/Newsroom/PressAnnouncements/ucm347087.htm United States] and [http://webprod5.hc-sc.gc.ca/dpd-bdpp/dispatch-repartition.do?lang=eng Canada], the doxylamine-pyridoxine combination (as Diclegis in US and Diclectin in Canada) is the only approved Pregnancy Category "A" prescription treatment for nausea and vomiting of pregnancy. 

[[Ondansetron]] may be beneficially however there are some concerns regarding an association with [[cleft palate]],<ref>{{cite journal|last=Koren|first=G|title=Motherisk update. Is ondansetron safe for use during pregnancy?|journal=Canadian family physician Medecin de famille canadien|date=2012 Oct|volume=58|issue=10|pages=1092–3|pmid=23064917}}</ref> and there is little high quality data.<ref name=BMJ2011/> [[Metoclopramide]] is also used and relatively well tolerated.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Tan|first=PC|coauthors=Omar, SZ|title=Contemporary approaches to hyperemesis during pregnancy.|journal=Current opinion in obstetrics & gynecology|date=2011 Apr|volume=23|issue=2|pages=87–93|pmid=21297474}}</ref> Evidence for the use of [[corticosteroid]]s is weak.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Poon|first=SL|title=Towards evidence-based emergency medicine: Best BETs from the Manchester Royal Infirmary. BET 2: Steroid therapy in the treatment of intractable hyperemesis gravidarum.|journal=Emergency medicine journal : EMJ|date=2011 Oct|volume=28|issue=10|pages=898–900|pmid=21918097}}</ref>

